g2:c.RULE.g2:a.TEXT: initially conclude that test-suite-name is example-tests
initially in order conclude that the number-of-passed-subtests of every benchmark-test-with-subtests = 0

g2:c.BORDERLESS-FREE-TEXT.g2:a.TEXT: The following procedures are used to report the test results of tests with subtests. For each subtest, call pass-subtest or fail-subtest, then at the end call subtests-complete.
The following parameter must be set by a initially rule (See tsdriver-documentation).

The parameter REG-UTILS-LOADED indicates whether it is a stand-alone test or a automated test. The procedures act according to its value. The parameter TESTS-FAILED is set whenever ther is a subtest failed. It determines whether the whole test is failed or passed. The rest of paramters are usually set to true.
The following procedures are used to report the test results
The following initially rule is used to start the test and determine whether this test is running stand-alone or via communication with master.

g2:c.USER-MENU-CHOICE.g2:a.LABEL: PERFORM-TEST
g2:c.USER-MENU-CHOICE.g2:a.ACTION: in order start initialize-benchmark-node-2 (the item) and start test-procedure-starter (the item) after 1 second

g2:c.BORDERLESS-FREE-TEXT.g2:a.TEXT: The propagation of activations from one test to the next will be performed by start-benchmark-node. This will begin a threaded execution for this node and the connected nodes to this node. For start nodes it will merely start the nodes that are connected at its output (start-following-nodes), and change its report message. For test nodes it will call the test-procedure of the test and then start its following nodes. The end-flow node will call back to the master that the benchmark is completed, mark itself, and then stop if running under control of the master harness.
<-- It is like pass, but also change the text of the report message.

g2:c.RULE.g2:a.TEXT: initially in order conclude that reg-utils-loaded = (if there exists a procedure PR such that (the name of PR exists and the name of PR is log-trouble) then the symbol yes else the symbol no) and start begin-test () after 2 seconds

g2:c.READOUT-TABLE.g2:a.EXPRESSION-TO-DISPLAY: the sum over each benchmark-test T of ((if the number-of-passed-subtests N of T exists then the number-of-subtests of T - N else (if the test-result of T is passed then 0 else 1)))

g2:c.ACTION-BUTTON.g2:a.LABEL: Show improved tests
g2:c.ACTION-BUTTON.g2:a.ACTION:
for any benchmark-test NODE
when the test-result of NODE is passed and the previous-test-result of the test-result of NODE is not passed {spliced-out tests have no attached message} and there exists a message msg that is the-report-of NODE
then inform the operator that "[the name of NODE] regressed: [the text of msg]"

g2:c.ACTION-BUTTON.g2:a.LABEL: Show regressed tests
g2:c.ACTION-BUTTON.g2:a.ACTION:
for any benchmark-test NODE
when the test-result of NODE is not passed and the previous-test-result of the test-result of NODE is passed
then inform the operator that "[the name of NODE] regressed: [(if there exists a message msg that is the-report-of NODE then the text of msg else "test not run")]"

g2:c.BORDERLESS-FREE-TEXT.g2:a.TEXT: ### Load file-io-module before using following buttons ###

g2:c.ACTION-BUTTON.g2:a.LABEL: Show failed tests
g2:c.ACTION-BUTTON.g2:a.ACTION:
for any benchmark-test NODE
when the test-result of NODE is not passed and there exists a message msg that is the-report-of NODE
then inform the operator that "[the name of NODE] failed: [the text of msg]"

g2:c.READOUT-TABLE.g2:a.EXPRESSION-TO-DISPLAY: the sum over each benchmark-test T of ((if the number-of-subtests N of T exists then N else 1))
(if there exists a benchmark-test such that (the test-result of the benchmark-test is not passed) then "Fail" else "Pass")

g2:c.BORDERLESS-FREE-TEXT.g2:a.TEXT:
Construction of new tests has been simplified. You can make a new test suite in one of two ways.
I. To make a new test suite by adapting this kb:
1. Name the test suite. Change the initial-value of the text-parameter test-suite-name.
2. Create tests. Simply create benchmark-tests for each item to be tested, name the benchmark-test, create a subworkspace of benchmark-test, and put a test procedure on this subworkspace (contents described below). It will be convenient to simply clone an existing test in most cases.
3. Specify test sequence. Create a start-flow and end-flow item. Then connect all the tests and the start-flow and end-flow using the stubs. Normally, this will snake about. Feel free to use several workspaces, tying them together with connection posts. Each test's workspace will be shown as the test is executed. You can run tests in parallel by forking the connections if so desired.
4. Options. Normally, you need not fill in anything other than a name for each benchmark-test as it will automatically look for a test procedure whose name is the benchmark-test-name with "-test" suffixed. You can override by specifying a particular procedure name if desired. Also the default expectation is that tests will pass. You can override this and specify Aborted and Timed-out as the expected-test-result, but Passed is the default. Be careful when cloning other tests here. Finally, you can specify a different timeout limit.
5. Test procedure contents. These are arbitrary. It is suggested that you use the pass and fail procedures as in the example on the subworkspace of the example below. (If you choose not to use pass/fail, then you will need to conclude a new value for the test-result of the test to something other than not-yet-run since control propagation always runs all tests that are not-yet-run and that are connected to the currently completed test. With timeout or abort, the driver will automatically set this slot for you, so you don't have to trap errors, etc.) Pass and Fail will automatically notify the master test harness if this test is run as a regression test. (It is not necessary to change anything to run stand-alone.) They also annotate the workspace with test results.
6. Delete the existing example-tests workspace to eliminate existing tests. - erb 19 Sep 91

II. You can also make a new test suite by using REQUIRE of this module into your test suite. (This is preferred to the above.) To do this:
1. Provide an initially rule to conclude a value for text parameter test-suite-name.
2. Procede as above.
